It is to be noted here that as nitro-aerini particles cause the fermentation of the blood, so this fermenta- tion strikes out, in the way shown above, and draws from the air other nitro-aerial particles by which fer- mentation goes on anew in the blood. In fact nitro· acrial spirits, when mixed with the mass of the blood in the lungs, produce an intense enough effervescence in it; but they are soon separated for the most part from the blood in the system of the body, for purposcs to be explained below; so that the fermentation of the blood on its return to the lungs is for want of them much diminished and more sluggish3 but still it does not cease so completely as to be unable to draw nitro-aerial particles from the air lor its renewal.
